Lots of people here remember well how racked with fear they were in the weeks and days leading up to the 1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens, the volcano that rained utter havoc from 30 miles away on this tiny town.
Meanwhile, visitors' centers and viewing points on the mountain -- the one closest to the mountain's crater was closed and evacuated on Saturday -- have continued to register record numbers of tourists, many of them traveling long distances, carting cameras, generators, coolers and other provisions, and situating themselves on the mountain in an obsessive quest to watch it blow.
